  "prompt": "What's the best way to calculate percentage off of something?",
  "response": "Calculating a percentage off of an item is straightforward. Here\u2019s a simple step-by-step method to do it:\n\n1. **Determine the original price**: Identify the original price of the item.\n\n2. **Identify the discount percentage**: Determine the percentage that is being offered as a discount.\n\n3. **Calculate the amount of discount**:\n   - Use the formula: \n     \\[\n     \\text{Discount Amount} = \\text{Original Price} \\times \\left(\\frac{\\text{Discount Percentage}}{100}\\right)\n     \\]\n\n4. **Subtract the discount from the original price to find the sale price**: \n   - Use the formula:\n     \\[\n     \\text{Sale Price} = \\text{Original Price} - \\text{Discount Amount}\n     \\]\n\n### Example\nIf you have an item that costs $50 and there is a 20% discount:\n\n1. **Original Price**: $50\n2. **Discount Percentage**: 20%\n3. **Calculate Discount Amount**:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Discount Amount} = 50 \\times \\left(\\frac{20}{100}\\right) = 50 \\times 0.20 = 10\n   \\]\n4. **Calculate Sale Price**:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Sale Price} = 50 - 10 = 40\n   \\]\n\nSo, after applying a 20% discount, the sale price of the item would be $40.",
